      "output": "The sky appears blue because of a phenomenon called **Rayleigh scattering**.\n\n1. **Sunlight is made of many colors** \u2013 When white sunlight reaches Earth, it contains a mixture of all visible wavelengths (red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, violet).\n\n2. **The atmosphere isn\u2019t empty** \u2013 The air is filled with tiny molecules of nitrogen, oxygen, and other gases, as well as small particles.\n\n3. **Shorter wavelengths scatter more** \u2013 When light hits these tiny molecules, it gets scattered in different directions. The amount of scattering depends on the wavelength: shorter wavelengths (blue and violet) are scattered about **10\u202ftimes more** than longer wavelengths (red, orange). This is described by Rayleigh\u2019s scattering law, which says the scattering intensity varies inversely with the fourth power of wavelength (\u221d\u202f1/\u03bb\u2074).\n\n4. **Our eyes see blue, not violet** \u2013 Although violet light is scattered even more than blue, our eyes are less sensitive to violet and a lot of it is absorbed by the upper atmosphere. The combination of scattered blue light reaching us from all directions makes the sky look predominantly blue.\n\n5. **Why sunrise and sunset are red** \u2013 When the Sun is low on the horizon, its light must travel through a much thicker layer of atmosphere. The blue light gets scattered out long before the light reaches your eyes, leaving the longer\u2011wavelength reds and oranges to dominate the sky\u2019s color.\n\nIn short, the sky is blue because Earth\u2019s atmosphere scatters shorter\u2011wavelength (blue) sunlight more efficiently than the longer wavelengths, and our eyes perceive that scattered blue light coming from every direction.",
